{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01Ff2PZP7oFso7Y9aAmYZ7Ms","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_012HAd9QD6JbKxdq2uzcJzz2","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"All direct and transitive dependencies are extracted from the manifest and included in the vulnerability check.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure here is: does the code actually parse the manifest file correctly and extract ALL dependencies (direct + transitive)? A Unit test with pre-parsed data would miss file parsing bugs, encoding issues, or format-specific edge cases. You need real file I/O and the full parsing pipeline working together to catch when the manifest reading or dependency graph traversal breaks.","test_description":"Create test manifest files (package.json, requirements.txt, etc.) with known dependency graphs. Load each manifest through the full extraction pipeline, verify that all direct and transitive dependencies are identified. Test edge cases: circular dependencies, nested lockfiles, conditional dependencies.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The vulnerability database query returns results that match the exact version ranges in the manifest, not just the package name.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is: does the code construct and send a query that includes version information, and does it correctly handle version-specific responses? You need to verify the code sends the right query parameters (not just 'package foo', but 'package foo @1.2.3 or @^1.2.0'). Mocking the API response alone is not enough—you must wire the manifest parser, query builder, and API client together and verify the query includes version data.","test_description":"Integrate manifest parsing with query construction. Mock the vulnerability API and capture the actual request parameters. Verify that version information is included in each query (exact version or range). Test with manifests specifying different version constraints (exact, range, caret, tilde) and verify each generates the correct query.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The severity sorting places Critical above High above Medium above Low, with CVEs of the same severity sorted by CVSS score.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is a pure sorting algorithm. The test receives a list of CVE objects with severity and CVSS score fields, and verifies the output list is ordered correctly. There is no I/O, no external dependencies, no database—just data transformation. A Unit test passing pre-constructed CVE objects is sufficient to catch sorting bugs.","test_description":"Create test CVE objects with various combinations of severity levels (Critical, High, Medium, Low) and CVSS scores. Pass them to the sort function and verify the output order: Critical entries first, then High, then Medium, then Low; within each severity band, verify CVSS scores are descending. Use parametrized tests to cover all severity pairs and edge cases (tied scores, missing scores).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.95,"Integration":0.05,"System":0,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The manifest modification changes only the affected dependency's version, leaving all other entries unchanged.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure is: does the code read the manifest file, modify only the target dependency, and write it back without corrupting other entries? File format specifics matter (JSON indentation, YAML anchors, line-ending preservation, comment handling). A Unit test with pre-parsed objects would miss file format bugs and side effects. You need end-to-end file I/O to catch when the code mangles the file.","test_description":"Create test manifest files with multiple dependencies and various formatting details (comments, indentation, trailing whitespace). Load each manifest, request a modification to one dependency's version, then verify the file is written back with only that dependency changed. Validate that formatting is preserved, comments remain, and other entries are untouched. Test with realistic manifests (with many deps).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.85,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The auto-generated pull request is created on the real repository with the correct single-dependency diff.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The failure is: does a PR actually get created on the real repository with the right diff? This is a real external API call to GitHub (or similar). While you could mock the GitHub API at Integration level, catching the real failure—that the PR is malformed, the authentication fails, or the repository is in an unexpected state—requires testing against a real repository or a realistic test double. The phrase 'created on the real repository' indicates the test must exercise real GitHub API behavior.","test_description":"Create a test repository on a real instance (or use GitHub's test/sandbox if available). Run the PR creation code against this test repo with a manifest change. Verify the PR is created, is mergeable, has exactly one dependency change in the diff, and has no unintended side effects. Inspect the actual GitHub PR object to confirm correctness. Optionally use a mock GitHub API server (e.g., locally-run server mimicking GitHub API) if integration-level mocking is preferred.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.35,"System":0.65,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A major version bump is correctly identified as a breaking change based on semver comparison.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is a pure semantic versioning comparison algorithm. Given two version strings, the code determines if upgrading is a breaking change (major version increase = breaking). No I/O, no external calls, just string parsing and comparison logic. A Unit test with version pairs is sufficient to catch comparison bugs.","test_description":"Create parametrized test cases for semver comparisons: (old_version, new_version, is_breaking). Cover: major bumps (1.0.0 → 2.0.0, breaking=true), minor bumps (1.2.0 → 1.3.0, breaking=false), patch bumps (1.2.3 → 1.2.4, breaking=false), pre-release versions, and edge cases (v1 vs 1.0.0, missing minor/patch). Verify each pair is correctly classified.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.95,"Integration":0.05,"System":0,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When a breaking change is detected, PR creation is skipped and a review flag is surfaced in the scanner output.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The real failure is: code detects a breaking change correctly but still creates a PR anyway (control flow bug). Or it detects breaking change but doesn't set the review flag. A Unit test of the breaking change detection or flag setting in isolation would miss the integration bug where the control flow doesn't actually prevent PR creation. You need to verify that when breaking_change=true, the GitHub API is NOT called. This requires wiring the breaking change detector + PR creation logic together and mocking the API to spy on whether it gets called.","test_description":"Test the full flow: detect breaking change, attempt PR creation, verify the GitHub API mock is never invoked, and verify the review flag is present and true in the output. Use a mocked GitHub client to spy on calls. Test with multiple scenarios: non-breaking change (API called, flag false), breaking change (API not called, flag true). Verify the output JSON/report structure includes the review flag.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":13395,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a7de1800-6615-4eb4-8f43-8c7676bea979","uuid":"80f38627-0729-4a39-9d92-f463768465f6"}
